<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="fermatslittletheorem" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Fermat's Little Theorem</title>

  <p>
    The next topic we will consider is a result known as "Fermat's Little Theorem".
    Pierre de Fermat was a mathematician in the 17th century who extensively studied number theory, and is perhaps best know for his "Last Theorem".
    Fermat's little theorem is a key result in number theory that is a major ingredient in the study of primality testing and encryption algorithms, which you can learn more about in the course MA 340. 
  </p>

  <p>
    We will begin with the following experiments using either a calculator on your phone or using SageMath.
    Suppose that <m>p</m> is a prime number, and suppose <m>a</m> is a positive integer that is relatively prime to <m>p</m>.
    In symbols, <m>p\nmid a</m>.
    <alert>Is there a value <m>x</m> that consistently gives <me>[a]^x=[1] \, ?</me></alert>
    In other words, is there a value of <m>x</m> that will always guarantee 
    <md>
      a^x\equiv 1 \bmod p \, ?
    </md>
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      For each of the following values of <m>p</m> and <m>a</m>, use a calculator or SageMath or another computer system to calculate 
      <m>
        [a]^x
      </m>
      for each <m>x=1,2,3,\ldots,p</m>.
      In other words, what is the remainder of <m>a^x</m> after dividing by <m>p</m>?
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p=3, a=8</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p=7, a=306</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
          <m>p=17, a = 14</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p=11, a=13^{10^{100}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    From this, there are two things to observe.
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          First, we see that it appears that <m>x=p-1</m> always produces <m>[1]</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Second, we see that it is hard to check this for all integers.
          In particular, if <m>p</m> and <m>a</m> are both extremely large, then they cannot be stored in the memory of a computer.
          Thus, if we think that <m>x=p-1</m> always produces <m>[1]</m>, we need to prove it.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    This leads us to our main result.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-fermatlittletheorem">
    <title>Fermat's Little Theorem</title>    
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>p</m> is prime and <m>a</m> is a positive integer such that <m>p</m> does not divide <m>a</m>, then
        <md>
          [a]^{p-1} = [1] \, .
        </md>
        Equivalently,
        <md>
          a^{p-1}\equiv 1 \bmod p \, .
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    We will give two proofs of Fermat's little theorem.
    Our first proof relies on properties of units in <m>\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}</m>.
    We will use the notation <m>A\setminus B</m>, read as "A setminus B", to denote the elements of <m>A</m> that are not in <m>B</m>.
  </p>

  <proof>
    <title>Proof of Fermat's Little Theorem using units</title>
    <p>
      We begin our proof with the claim that every non-zero element <m>[a]\in \mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m> is a unit, since every such <m>a</m> has <m>\gcd(a,p)=1</m>.
      Thus, for any such <m>[a]</m>, the function <m>M_a</m> that sends <m>[b]\in \mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m> to <m>[a][b]</m> is an invertible function from <m>\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\setminus \{[0]\}</m> to itself.
      In other words, 
      <me>M_a:\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\setminus \{[0]\} \rightarrow \mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\setminus \{[0]\}</me>
      is a function that is both one-to-one and onto.
      Therefore, <m>M_a</m> rearranges the elements of <m>\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We prove this claim as follows.
      First, suppose that for <m>[b]</m> and <m>[b']</m> we have <m>[a][b]=[a][b']</m>.
      Then multiplying both sides by <m>[a]^{-1}</m> we obtain <m>[b]=[b']</m>, and thus the function is one-to-one.
      Second, we want to show that <m>M_a</m> is onto, i.e., that every element of <m>\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m> is mapped onto by <m>M_a</m>.
      Suppose that <m>[b]\in\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m>.
      Then we know that <m>[a]^{-1}[b]\in\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}</m>.
      So, <me>M_a([a]^{-1}[b])=[a][a]^{-1}[b]=[b] \, ,</me> showing that <m>[b]</m> is mapped onto by <m>M_a</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus, we see that
      <md>
        \{[1],[2],[3],\ldots,[p-1]\}=\{[a][1],[a][2],[a][3],\ldots,[a][p-1]\} \, .
      </md>
      Hence, we have that the product of all the elements in the first set is equal to the product of all the elements in the second set, i.e.,
      <md>
        [1][2][3]\cdots [p-1] = [a][1][a][2][a][3]\cdots [a][p-1] \, .
      </md>
      Multiplying both sides by <me>[1]^{-1}[2]^{-1}[3]^{-1}\cdots [p-1]^{-1}</me> we obtain
      <md>
        [1]=[a]^{p-1}
      </md>
      and this completes the proof.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Work through the details of this proof in the specific case of <m>p=7, a=3</m>.
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Discuss the above proof. Does it make sense? Why or why not?
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Our second proof uses a combinatorial argument, i.e., a proof based on counting.
  </p>

    <proof>
    <title>Combinatorial proof of Fermat's Little Theorem</title>
    <p>
      We will prove that for <alert>any</alert> positive integer <m>a</m> we have
      <md>
        a^p\equiv a \bmod p \, ,
      </md>
      and thus in the special case where <m>\gcd(a,p)=1</m>, we can cancel <m>a</m> from both sides to obtain our desired formula
      <md>
        a^{p-1}\equiv 1 \bmod p \, .
      </md>
      Observe that <m>a^p</m> counts the number of length <m>p</m> "words" that we can write using <m>a</m> letters.
      For example, if <m>p=3</m> and <m>a=3</m>, then there are <m>3^3=27</m> words of length three using the three letters <m>\{a,b,c\}</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>aaa,aab,aac</mrow>
        <mrow>aba,abb,abc</mrow>
        <mrow>aca,acb,acc</mrow>
        <mrow>baa,bab,bac</mrow>
        <mrow>bba,bbb,bbc</mrow>
        <mrow>bca,bcb,bcc</mrow>
        <mrow>caa,cba,cca</mrow>
        <mrow>cba,cbb,cbc</mrow>
        <mrow>cca,ccb,ccc</mrow>
      </md>
      We need to show that <me>p\mid a^p-a</me>.
      Observe that <m>a^p-a</m> is the number of words remaining after we delete all the single-letter words.
      In our above example, if we remove <m>aaa</m>, <m>bbb</m>, and <m>ccc</m> from the list then there are <m>3^3-3</m> words remaining.
      To show that <m>p</m> divides <m>a^p-a</m>, we need to gather the remaining words into groups of size <m>p</m>.
      The way we will do this is to gather the words when they agree by a cyclic shift, i.e., starting from a word create a list of <m>p</m> words by repeatedly taking the last letter and moving it to the first position.
      For example, when <m>p=7</m> we will group the words in the following list, where the next word is obtained by moving the last letter to the front of the next word:
      <md>
        <mrow>abcabac</mrow>
        <mrow>cabcaba</mrow>
        <mrow>acabcab</mrow>
        <mrow>bacabca</mrow>
        <mrow>abacabc</mrow>
        <mrow>cabacab</mrow>
        <mrow>bcabaca</mrow>
      </md>
      The length of our words is prime, and therefore we never see a repeated word in this list (since that would create a divisor of <m>p</m>).
      Thus, this method gathers all of the <m>a^p-a</m> words into groups of size <m>p</m>, and hence <m>p</m> divides <m>a^p-a</m>, as desired.
    </p>
  </proof>
  
<exercise>
  <p>
    Discuss the above proof. Does it make sense? Why or why not?
  </p>
</exercise>

<p>
  Let's watch a <url href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OoQ16YCYksw">video from Khan Academy</url> that gives a 6-minute explanation of the combinatorial proof of Fermat's Little Theorem.
</p>

<exercise>
  <p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
        Discuss the video with your group. Does it make the proof more clear? Why or why not?
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Discuss the various aspects of embodied, symbolic, and formal mathematical reasoning that has appeared in the various proofs of Fermat's Little Theorem that we have seen. What were positives and negatives of each proof and of the video?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</exercise>


</section>